[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    101[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mLocation:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m Why-These-Services "Amazon Kinesis Data Streams (or Amazon MSK) for the EHR event feed" paragraph; Architecture Diagram ([38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mA[EHR vitals feed | HL7/FHIR] --> B[Amazon Kinesis | clinical-events][38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m); Prerequisites EHR Integration row ("Real-time ingest typically requires HL7 v2 ADT, ORU (results), ORM (orders), or FHIR R4 subscriptions").[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    102[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mProblem:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m The EHR-to-AWS ingress is the PHI surface for the largest single data flow in this architecture. The recipe describes the ingest at a high level but doesn't specify the EHR-side authentication and encryption protocol (HL7 v2 over MLLP-with-TLS for the legacy path; FHIR R4 subscriptions over HTTPS with mutual TLS or OAuth for the modern path), the AWS-side ingress endpoint (API Gateway with mutual TLS authentication for FHIR; on-premises MLLP listener republishing to Kinesis or MSK for HL7 v2), the trading-partner agreement discipline that governs the EHR-to-payer or EHR-to-aggregator relationship, the on-premises-to-AWS network path (Direct Connect for production volumes; Site-to-Site VPN for lower-volume or pilot), and the integration-engine layer (Mirth Connect, Rhapsody, Cloverleaf, vendor-supplied integration engines) that the Prerequisites row correctly names but doesn't tie to the security posture.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    103[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    104[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106mSame finding shape as Recipe 3.4 S3 (HL7 v2 ingress for medication dispensing), Recipe 3.5 S4 (MLLP bridge for lab results), Recipe 3.6 S6 (837 EDI ingress for claims). The recurring ingress-security pattern is now a strong candidate for a healthcare-integration-engineer appendix.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    105[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mFix:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m Add an EHR-ingress-security paragraph to the Why-These-Services Kinesis paragraph: "The EHR-to-AWS ingress is the PHI surface for the largest single data flow in this architecture. For the HL7 v2 path: MLLP-over-TLS (MLLPS) with mutual TLS authentication; on-premises MLLP listener deployed in a DMZ or integration tier (not on the clinical network); republish to Kinesis or MSK via VPC PrivateLink endpoint; trading partner agreement covering the on-premises-to-AWS handoff. For the FHIR R4 path: HTTPS with mutual TLS or OAuth-with-asymmetric-client-auth (per the SMART on FHIR backend services profile); FHIR Subscription resources delivered to an API Gateway endpoint with mutual TLS authentication backed by Lambda. Direct Connect for production volumes; Site-to-Site VPN acceptable for pilot deployments. Integration engine layer (Mirth Connect, Rhapsody, Cloverleaf, vendor-supplied) is part of the BAA discipline; the BAA covers the AWS-side handling and the integration engine's BAA-or-equivalent agreement covers the on-premises pre-aggregation handling. CloudTrail data events on every PutRecord into Kinesis or PutRecords into MSK; Kinesis SSE with customer-managed KMS keys; the ingress Lambda runs in a VPC with no public egress." Add to Prerequisites EHR Integration row a security-posture clause covering MLLPS for legacy ingress and SMART-on-FHIR backend services for modern ingress.[K
