[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    148[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mLocation:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m Step 8 [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mon_clinical_outcome[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m (consumed via EventBridge from clinical-event publishers and from the EHR-events stream); Architecture Diagram ([38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mAE[Outcome events | ICU transfer / Code / Sepsis bundle] --> AF[AWS Lambda | outcome-capture][38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m); Step 8 [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mon_clinician_acknowledgment[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m (similar event-driven path).[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    149[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mProblem:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m The architecture is event-driven from the EHR for outcome events (ICU transfers, code blues, sepsis bundle initiations, unexpected deaths, discharges) and from the clinician-facing UI for acknowledgment events. EventBridge guarantees at-least-once delivery; Lambda asynchronous invocation also retries on failure. If EventBridge redelivers an outcome event (the Lambda's first attempt timed out, the EHR-events publisher's PutEvents call retried after a transient error, or any of the failure modes documented in the recurring trigger-idempotency findings across Recipes 2.4-2.10 and 3.1-3.6), [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mon_clinical_outcome[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m runs twice on the same outcome. Each run:[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    150[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    151[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106m1[38;2;191;97;106m.[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mSearches OpenSearch for recent alerts on the patient and links the outcome to each.[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m The OpenSearch search is idempotent in shape, but the linkage update writes [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140malert.outcome[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m on each matching alert with a [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mtime_from_alert_to_outcome_minutes[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m value derived from [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140moutlier_event_id[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m and [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140moutcome_event.occurred_at[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m. A redelivered event with a slightly different timestamp overwrites the linkage timestamp inconsistently; downstream metrics (mean time-from-alert-to-outcome, alert-precision-by-outcome-type) get noisy.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    152[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    153[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106m2[38;2;191;97;106m.[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mWrites a fresh label row to S3 with a UUID-keyed path[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m ([38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mS3.PutObject(... key = f"outcomes/year={...}/month={...}/{generate_id()}.json", ...)[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m). Two label rows for the same outcome get picked up by the next quarterly retraining job. This biases the supervised classifier's training distribution toward whichever cases happened to be redelivered.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    154[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    155[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106m3[38;2;191;97;106m.[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mRe-fetches recent alerts[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m (the [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mOpenSearch.Search[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m call). This is the expensive operation; redelivery doubles the cost without producing additional value.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    156[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    157[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106mSame recurring trigger-idempotency pattern as Recipes 2.4-2.10, 3.1, 3.2, 3.3, 3.4, 3.5, 3.6 (twelfth consecutive recipe). The fix template is the same.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    158[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    159[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106mFor Recipe 3.7 specifically the consequence is calibrated to the supervised-retraining pathway: doubled label rows on positive cases distort the supervised classifier's class-balance and produce a model that over-fires on patterns that happen to have been redelivered during the training window. For a deterioration model where the positive class is rare (ICU transfers happen at most a few percent of admissions) and labels are precious, doubled labels on a minority of cases are a meaningful training-distribution artifact that propagates into production scoring. With this finding now flagged across twelve consecutive recipes, the cookbook editor should treat the trigger-idempotency appendix as the highest-leverage cookbook-wide editorial investment. The per-recipe editorial loop is producing diminishing returns.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    160[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mFix:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m Two-part fix:[K
