[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    336[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mLocation:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m Why-These-Services "AWS HealthLake or a custom FHIR repository for the longitudinal patient record" paragraph; Architecture Diagram (HealthLake is not shown explicitly in the diagram); Prerequisites table (HealthLake is named in the AWS Services row).[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    337[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mProblem:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m AWS HealthLake is named as an optional store for FHIR-formatted longitudinal patient records, with the right framing ("For deployments with established FHIR infrastructure, HealthLake is a strong choice. For deployments that interface directly with EHR data via HL7 v2 or proprietary feeds, a custom FHIR transformation layer plus DynamoDB / S3 storage may fit better"). But the HealthLake-specific networking and access-control posture is not specified: HealthLake datastores can be configured with KMS encryption (customer-managed or AWS-managed), the datastore endpoint is regional and supports VPC endpoint access via [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mcom.amazonaws.{region}.healthlake[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m, FHIR resources can have resource-level access controls via SMART-on-FHIR scopes if HealthLake is used as the SMART-on-FHIR backend, and CloudTrail data events on HealthLake operations are part of the HIPAA audit posture.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    338[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    339[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106mFor a deployment that uses HealthLake as the longitudinal patient record store, the patient data the deterioration model reads to compute features and baselines lives in HealthLake; the HealthLake-specific posture matters as much as the DynamoDB and Timestream postures.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    340[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mFix:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m Expand the HealthLake paragraph: "For deployments using HealthLake: configure the FHIR datastore with customer-managed KMS encryption; access HealthLake via VPC endpoint ([38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mcom.amazonaws.{region}.healthlake[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m) so FHIR resource fetches don't traverse the public internet; CloudTrail data events on HealthLake [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mRead*[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m and [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mWrite*[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m operations capture the audit trail; if HealthLake is used as a SMART-on-FHIR backend, scope the OAuth client credentials (the deterioration-model service principal) to the minimum FHIR resource types and patient compartments needed (Observation for vitals and labs, MedicationAdministration for medication context, Encounter for admission and unit context, Patient for demographics; not Condition, Procedure, or DiagnosticReport unless those are explicitly used as features). HealthLake's bulk export to S3 supports the offline training pipeline; the export bucket must have customer-managed KMS encryption and lifecycle management aligned to the training data retention policy."[K
